    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Certificate-Less Message Authentication Protocols Using Pseudo-Id and Hash Chain</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Ashraph Sulaiman</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Authentication Protocols<br />Scalable Vanets</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Jul-2013 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0119</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Vehicular Networks is a promising approach to facilitate life safety in roads, traffic management,
and other useful information dissemination for driver community. In general, VANETs
are subclasses of mobile ad hoc networks (MANETs) in which vehicles are the mobile nodes
connected through wireless protocols.
However, practical implementation of vehicular communication is subject to various security
and privacy issues due to the scale of the network, high mobility nature and the sporadic
connectivity between them. Especially, performing source authentication efficiently with improved
performance and reduced costs for a high dense traffic, is merely impractical with
the available solutions. In addition, supporting both Vehicle-to-Vehicle(V2V) and Vehicle-to-
Infrastructure(V2I) communications is another challenge for many existing solutions, because
of the key management difficulties. Therefore, it is necessary to find a suitable solution to be
able to balance the need for security with the constraints of the network and the overheads
caused by such security requirements during either type of communications.
Therefore, the major concern was to propose an efficient protocol to support both Vehicleto-
Vehicle(V2V) and Vehicle-to-Infrastructure(V2I) communications with a significantly lower
overheads and satisfying scalability requirements. This thesis proposes a new approach that
can satisfy necessary security requirements of VANET with improved scalability and performance,
and at a significantly lower transmission delays and message losses. This thesis is
organized, as a framework of two sets of security protocols with improved features and performance
over one another. The first set of protocols are based on identity based cryptography
and the second set are based on one-way hash chain techniques. In each set, the second protocol
is the modified version of the first one. The new concept of periodic broadcasting of
an aggregated list of hash values by the Road Side Units is proposed, in order to eliminate
the certificate burdens of the vehicles. Moreover, batch verification of multiple signatures is
employed in the proposed protocols, to speed up the performance of the network to achieve
better scalability.
This framework was evaluated using Network Simulator (NS-2), to check whether the
desired objective was met. An extended analysis and evaluation of the proposed regime was
carried out that includes various security feature assessments, estimation of various overheads
such as computational, communication and storage overheads, comparing the scalability of
the proposed scheme with that of other popular protocols. Compared to the conventional
PKI scheme which is the current VANET standard, the proposed regime significantly reduces
the computational overhead by approximately 72% and the transmission delay by 93% even
for heavy traffic situations. Therefore, it is believed that the proposed protocol will be more
scalable and outperform the existing solutions with an increased throughput and reduced overheads
for an efficient vehicular communication.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13825">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/13825</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
